WEBVTT

NOTE Draft word-boundary captions for Day 413 rough render v2; not final or uploaded.

00:00:00.102 --> 00:00:02.769
A good AI answer can still arrive too
early.

00:00:03.516 --> 00:00:09.109
You ask a question. The model gives a
fluent paragraph, a clean plan, maybe

00:00:09.149 --> 00:00:12.420
even a reasonable recommendation.

00:00:13.151 --> 00:00:18.198
It feels like progress. But sometimes the
answer is solving a question you

00:00:18.238 --> 00:00:22.905
have not finished asking. This video is
about slowing the first answer down

00:00:22.945 --> 00:00:27.224
just enough to keep the human parts of the
decision visible.

00:00:27.956 --> 00:00:32.123
By the end, you will have one prompt you
can reuse before any important AI

00:00:32.163 --> 00:00:37.628
answer. It checks three things: Goal.

00:00:38.333 --> 00:00:40.844
Grounding. Ownership.

00:00:41.562 --> 00:00:45.818
What are we trying to do? What facts would
change the answer?

00:00:46.550 --> 00:00:50.037
And what parts are still mine to choose?

00:00:50.781 --> 00:00:53.214
Think of the model as a bright worktable.

00:00:53.945 --> 00:00:56.196
It can lay out options and tradeoffs.

00:00:56.927 --> 00:01:01.430
But the worktable should not decide what
the work is for.

00:01:02.760 --> 00:01:04.685
Start with a small example.

00:01:05.418 --> 00:01:09.492
You ask: Should I redesign this onboarding
page?

00:01:10.236 --> 00:01:15.130
The model might say: simplify the page,
reduce friction, test a clearer button.

00:01:15.874 --> 00:01:17.291
Useful, maybe.

00:01:18.036 --> 00:01:20.429
But it is answering a half-built question.

00:01:21.161 --> 00:01:25.521
Does better mean more signups, fewer
confused users, fewer support tickets,

00:01:25.561 --> 00:01:28.762
or a more honest first impression?

00:01:29.494 --> 00:01:34.707
Those are different goals. If you do not
name the goal, the model may quietly

00:01:34.747 --> 00:01:37.096
name it for you.

00:01:37.814 --> 00:01:42.434
So the first checkpoint is Goal: what am I
actually trying to decide or create?

00:01:43.153 --> 00:01:46.861
Not just make this better. Better for
whom?

00:01:47.580 --> 00:01:51.276
Better by what measure? Better at what
cost?

00:01:52.020 --> 00:01:56.546
This applies beyond product work: a
purchase, a job choice, a family plan,

00:01:56.586 --> 00:01:57.552
a hard email.

00:01:58.296 --> 00:02:02.486
Once the target is visible, the model can
help without inventing the game.

00:02:03.786 --> 00:02:05.724
The second checkpoint is Grounding.

00:02:06.457 --> 00:02:09.554
Ask: what real-world facts would change
the answer?

00:02:10.273 --> 00:02:14.861
If the model recommends a redesign, what
would make that recommendation stronger

00:02:14.901 --> 00:02:16.885
or weaker?

00:02:17.603 --> 00:02:20.270
Maybe users drop off at the second step.

00:02:20.989 --> 00:02:25.648
Maybe support tickets mention the same
confusing sentence.

00:02:26.366 --> 00:02:29.137
Maybe people hesitate over a price detail.

00:02:29.856 --> 00:02:32.367
Or maybe the page is not the real problem.

00:02:33.111 --> 00:02:38.266
So instead of only asking, explain your
reasoning, try asking: What evidence

00:02:38.306 --> 00:02:40.088
would change your recommendation?

00:02:40.806 --> 00:02:44.867
Separate what you know from what you are
assuming.

00:02:45.585 --> 00:02:48.565
That turns the answer into a checklist for
reality.

00:02:49.884 --> 00:02:52.890
This is a small habit, not a safety
guarantee.

00:02:53.636 --> 00:02:57.654
Decision-support researchers have long
studied cases where people lean too

00:02:57.694 --> 00:03:00.900
hard on automated recommendations.

00:03:01.618 --> 00:03:06.498
In some human-AI studies, explanations
changed how people relied on a system.

00:03:07.243 --> 00:03:12.657
They did not reliably help people spot
which recommendations were correct.

00:03:13.402 --> 00:03:16.954
So the point is not: ask for an
explanation and relax.

00:03:17.686 --> 00:03:22.293
The point is: make the goal, assumptions,
evidence, and value choices visible

00:03:22.333 --> 00:03:25.235
before the advice feels settled.

00:03:26.526 --> 00:03:28.477
The third checkpoint is Ownership.

00:03:29.210 --> 00:03:32.698
Some parts of a decision are not facts the
model can discover.

00:03:33.429 --> 00:03:38.674
They depend on values, context,
responsibility, and risk.

00:03:39.406 --> 00:03:44.667
Suppose you write: Draft an email telling
a collaborator I am unhappy that

00:03:44.707 --> 00:03:49.078
the timeline is slipping. The model can
produce a polished email.

00:03:49.809 --> 00:03:52.307
But it does not know what you want to
protect.

00:03:53.039 --> 00:03:58.258
Do you want to repair trust, set a boundary,
get a new date, or document accountability?

00:03:59.002 --> 00:04:02.411
A gentle version may preserve warmth but
blur the boundary.

00:04:03.156 --> 00:04:07.789
A firm version may create clarity but
raise the temperature.

00:04:08.520 --> 00:04:10.523
A direct version may do both.

00:04:11.268 --> 00:04:13.818
The model can show versions side by side.

00:04:14.562 --> 00:04:17.255
You choose what you are willing to stand
behind.

00:04:17.986 --> 00:04:23.428
A better request is: Before drafting, list
the possible goals of this message

00:04:23.468 --> 00:04:26.500
and the relationship risks of each.

00:04:27.218 --> 00:04:30.706
Then give three versions: gentle, direct,
and firm.

00:04:31.450 --> 00:04:35.536
Separate tone choices from factual claims.

00:04:36.281 --> 00:04:38.805
Now the model is doing work on the table.

00:04:39.536 --> 00:04:42.073
You are still responsible for the
decision.

00:04:43.392 --> 00:04:48.796
Here is the whole habit as one prompt:
Before answering, help me keep ownership

00:04:48.836 --> 00:04:49.811
of this decision.

00:04:50.556 --> 00:04:53.431
1. Restate the goal you think I am
pursuing.

00:04:54.175 --> 00:04:57.559
2. List the facts or evidence that would
change your answer.

00:04:58.303 --> 00:05:03.522
3. Identify which parts depend on my
values, context, or risk tolerance.

00:05:04.254 --> 00:05:08.027
Then give advice, separating assumptions
from recommendations.

00:05:08.759 --> 00:05:10.944
That does not make the model correct.

00:05:11.675 --> 00:05:14.199
But it gives you three places to
intervene.

00:05:14.944 --> 00:05:17.251
If the goal is wrong, correct it.

00:05:17.808 --> 00:05:20.611
If the evidence is missing, go look for
it.

00:05:21.181 --> 00:05:25.944
If the answer depends on values, stop
pretending it is only a technical question.

00:05:27.258 --> 00:05:30.368
Try it on the next AI request that
actually matters.

00:05:31.101 --> 00:05:33.300
Paste the prompt before your question.

00:05:34.044 --> 00:05:39.784
Let the model fill in the goal, the
evidence, and the value-dependent parts.

00:05:40.502 --> 00:05:44.185
Then edit those three answers before you
accept the recommendation.

00:05:44.929 --> 00:05:45.969
Wrong goal?

00:05:46.700 --> 00:05:49.563
Fix it. Missing evidence?

00:05:50.294 --> 00:05:52.649
Look for it or lower your confidence.

00:05:53.367 --> 00:05:54.719
Value tradeoff?

00:05:55.450 --> 00:05:59.373
Pause. Smooth prose cannot choose that for
you.

00:05:59.956 --> 00:06:03.867
That is the difference between using AI to
think with you and letting it quietly

00:06:03.907 --> 00:06:06.664
finish the thinking for you.

00:06:07.836 --> 00:06:09.761
The point is not to think alone.

00:06:10.494 --> 00:06:15.388
A good model can widen the room: more
options, clearer tradeoffs, sharper questions,

00:06:15.416 --> 00:06:18.669
and a second pass on your reasoning.

00:06:19.414 --> 00:06:23.825
Use it for that. Use the model for options
and tradeoffs.

00:06:24.557 --> 00:06:29.125
Keep the goal, evidence, and final
judgment visible.

00:06:29.830 --> 00:06:34.151
Before you accept the answer, ask: What is
the goal?

00:06:34.882 --> 00:06:36.898
What would ground this in reality?

00:06:37.643 --> 00:06:39.516
What belongs to me to choose?

00:06:40.260 --> 00:06:42.276
Let the AI help you see more.

00:06:43.020 --> 00:06:45.544
Do not let it decide what seeing is for.
